In [[computational complexity theory]], '''DLOGTIME''' is the [[complexity class]] of all [[computational problem]]s solvable in a [[Logarithmic growth|logarithmic]] amount of [[computation time]] on a deterministic [[Turing machine]]. It must be defined on a [[random-access Turing machine]], since otherwise the input tape is longer than the range of cells that can be accessed by the machine. It is a very weak model of time complexity: no random-access Turing machine with a smaller deterministic time bound can access the whole input.<ref name="j">{{citation | last = Johnson | first = David S. | contribution = A catalog of complexity classes | mr = 1127168 | pages = 67–161 | publisher = Elsevier, Amsterdam | title = Handbook of theoretical computer science, Vol. A | year = 1990}}. See in particular [https://books.google.com/books?id=-X39_rA3VSQC&pg=PA140 p.&nbsp;140].</ref>
DLOGTIME-[[uniformity (complexity)|uniformity]] is important in [[circuit complexity]].<ref name="j"/><ref>{{citation | last1 = Allender | first1 = Eric | last2 = Gore | first2 = Vivek | contribution = On strong separations from AC<sup>0</sup> | mr = 1255326 | pages = 21–37 | publisher = Amer. Math. Soc., Providence, RI | series = DIMACS Ser. Discrete Math. Theoret. Comput. Sci. | title = Advances in computational complexity theory (New Brunswick, NJ, 1990) | volume = 13 | year = 1993}}. See in particular [https://books.google.com/books?id=qAl0aVP5VIkC&pg=PA23 p.&nbsp;23].</ref>
