{{unsolved|mathematics|Does forbidding both a tree and a clique as induced subgraphs produce graphs of bounded chromatic number?}} In [[graph theory]], the '''Gyárfás–Sumner conjecture''' asks whether, for every [[Tree (graph theory)|tree]] <math>T</math> and [[complete graph]] <math>K</math>, the graphs with neither <math>T</math> nor <math>K</math> as [[induced subgraph]]s have can be [[graph coloring|properly colored]] using only a constant number of colors. Equivalently, it asks whether the <math>T</math>-free graphs are [[χ-bounded|<math>\chi</math>-bounded]].{{r|s97}} It is named after [[András Gyárfás]] and [[David Sumner]], who formulated it independently in 1975 and 1981 respectively.{{r|g75|s81}} It remains unproven.{{r|cs14}}
In this conjecture, it is not possible to replace <math>T</math> by a graph with cycles. As [[Paul Erdős]] and [[András Hajnal]] have shown, there exist [[triangle-free graph]]s with arbitrarily large chromatic number and, at the same time, arbitrarily large [[girth (graph theory)|girth]].{{r|eh66}} Using these graphs, one can obtain graphs that avoid any fixed choice of a cyclic graph and clique (of more than two vertices) as induced subgraphs, and exceed any fixed bound on the chromatic number.{{r|s97}}
The conjecture is known to be true for certain special choices of <math>T</math>, including [[path graph|paths]],{{r|g87}} [[star (graph theory)|stars]], and trees of radius two.{{r|kp94}} It is also known that, for any tree <math>T</math>, the graphs that do not contain a [[Homeomorphism (graph theory)|subdivision]] of <math>T</math> are <math>\chi</math>-bounded.{{r|s97}}
