In mathematics, more specifically in [[chromatic homotopy theory]], the '''redshift conjecture''' states, roughly, that [[algebraic K-theory]] <math>K(R)</math> has chromatic level one higher than that of a complex-oriented [[ring spectrum]] ''R''.<ref>[http://math.mit.edu/conferences/talbot/2013/19-Lawson-thefuture.pdf Future directions], Tyler Lawson, April 27, 2013</ref> It was formulated by John Rognes in a lecture at Schloss Ringberg, Germany, in January 1999, and made more precise by him in a lecture at Mathematische Forschungsinstitut Oberwolfach, Germany, in September 2000.<ref>[http://folk.uio.no/rognes/papers/red-shift.pdf Algebraic K-theory of finitely presented ring spectra], John Rognes, September 29, 2000</ref> <ref>[http://oda.mfo.de/show/mfo/oda/Vortragsbuch/800/E20_00127/VB_SE20_00127_N126_P034.jpg MFO Vortragsbuch 126], Abstract</ref>
